    "narrative": "Today\u2019s slate for **Ghost Ride the WHIP** is headlined by **Mickey Moniak**, who leads our starting unit with an elite 75.98 score. **Moniak** benefits from a premium spot in the #2 hole and a massive +14% park adjustment, but crucially, he faces a pitcher with a 100% stolen base allowance rate, making him our primary engine for both runs and the scarcity category of SBs. Close behind, **Tyler Soderstrom** (72.72) and **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (72.09) are mandatory starts, both capitalizing on favorable matchups against Wacha and Martin. **Chisholm Jr.** is particularly interesting; despite a lower order position, his +15% SP skill leverage and dynamic platoon advantage make him a high-upside play, provided the rain in his matchup holds off.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision today was keeping **Alex Freeland** on the bench with a 58.63 score. While **Freeland** boasts strong park and pitching-skill advantages, his #9 spot in the order creates a negative efficiency drag that ultimately caused him to fall behind the higher-floor profiles of **Max Muncy** and **Luis Campusano**. We are also keeping a close eye on the 31% rain risk affecting **Vinnie Pasquantino**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, and **Giancarlo Stanton**. If the weather clears, **Pasquantino**\u2019s +14% dynamic platoon edge should play well, but he remains our most volatile asset given the wind-in factor. \n\nFinally, while we are prioritizing efficiency to preserve our game caps, we remain cognizant of our SB-scarcity strategy. **Corbin Carroll** (62.60) is starting despite a daunting matchup against a 3.09 xERA arm because his elite speed profile against a slow-delivering pitcher remains a priority. We have opted to bench **Jose Caballero** and **James Wood** despite their potential to swipe bags; their raw efficiency scores just couldn't crack the top-tier, even with the projected favorable game flows for **Wood** at the top of the order. We are banking on **Mickey Moniak**, **Brice 